            <fr:title text="Flow Matching: What, Why, and How?">Flow Matching: What, Why, and How?</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>This is a blog cataloging my understanding of <fr:link href="/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" title="Flow Matching for Generative Modeling" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" display-uri="lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023" type="local">Flow Matching for Generative Modeling</fr:link> prior to my group presentation on <fr:link href="/farebrotherTemporalDifferenceFlows2025/" title="Temporal Difference Flows" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/farebrotherTemporalDifferenceFlows2025/" display-uri="farebrotherTemporalDifferenceFlows2025" type="local">Temporal Difference Flows</fr:link>.</html:p><html:p><html:strong style="font-family: var(--sans); font-weight: 500;">Disclaimer.</html:strong> I came into this with literally no background. I have never even taken an ODE course. This may prove advantageous for the more general audience.</html:p>
  <fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>1</fr:day></fr:date><fr:title text="Motivation">Motivation</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
To understand flow matching, it is a useful endeavor to understand the problems in prior work it aims to solve.
<fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/B9J9/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>B9J9</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/B9J9/</fr:route><fr:title text="Normalizing Flows">Normalizing Flows</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>Brief notes on <fr:link href="/rezendeVariationalInferenceNormalizing/" title="Variational Inference with Normalizing Flows" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/rezendeVariationalInferenceNormalizing/" display-uri="rezendeVariationalInferenceNormalizing" type="local">Variational Inference with Normalizing Flows</fr:link> to motivate <fr:link href="/008A/" title="Flow Matching: What, Why, and How?" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008A/" display-uri="008A" type="local">flow matching</fr:link>.</html:p><html:p>We are concerned with the problem of <html:em>density estimation</html:em>. Given a dataset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {X}]]></fr:tex>, consisting of samples <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x}_i \sim  p(\mathbf {x})]]></fr:tex>, we want to learn <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(\mathbf {x})]]></fr:tex>. One popular way to do this is via <html:em>variational inference</html:em>. As a brief recap, in variational inference, we assume that there is actually a joint distribution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(\mathbf {x}, \mathbf {z})]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {z}]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="/0083/" title="Latent Variable" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/0083/" display-uri="0083" type="local">latent variable</fr:link>. We then find <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(\mathbf {x})]]></fr:tex> by maximizing the log-likelihood <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\log  \int  p(\mathbf {x} \mid  \mathbf {z}) \mathrm {d}\mathbf {z}]]></fr:tex></html:p><html:p>
 For an example of this, see my post on <fr:link href="/0088/" title="Expectation Maximization" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/0088/" display-uri="0088" type="local">expectation maximization</fr:link>. In that post, we utilize the <fr:link href="/0082/" title="Evidence Lower Bound" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/0082/" display-uri="0082" type="local">ELBO</fr:link> to learn a latent variable model <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q_{\phi }(\mathbf {z} | \mathbf {x})]]></fr:tex>. As discussed in my post on <fr:link href="/0082/" title="Evidence Lower Bound" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/0082/" display-uri="0082" type="local">ELBO</fr:link>, in order to learn <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(\mathbf {x})]]></fr:tex>, we must have that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(\mathbf {z} | \mathbf {x})]]></fr:tex> is in the family <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q_{\phi }]]></fr:tex>. However, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q_
 {\phi }]]></fr:tex> is usually a Gaussian parametrized by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi ]]></fr:tex>, so that we can easily learn <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi ]]></fr:tex>. In this case, it is very unlikely that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(\mathbf {z} \mid  x)]]></fr:tex> lies in the family of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q_{\phi }]]></fr:tex> and therefore we have no hope of learning the true <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(\mathbf {x})]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
<fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/PY9P/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>PY9P</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/PY9P/</fr:route><fr:title text="Continuous Normalizing Flows">Continuous Normalizing Flows</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p><fr:link href="/rezendeVariationalInferenceNormalizing/" title="Variational Inference with Normalizing Flows" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/rezendeVariationalInferenceNormalizing/" display-uri="rezendeVariationalInferenceNormalizing" type="local">Variational Inference with Normalizing Flows</fr:link>, <fr:link href="/chenNeuralOrdinaryDifferential/" title="Neural Ordinary Differential Equations" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/chenNeuralOrdinaryDifferential/" display-uri="chenNeuralOrdinaryDifferential" type="local">Neural Ordinary Differential Equations</fr:link></html:p>
  <fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:title text="What is this \det  factor?">What is this <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\det ]]></fr:tex> factor?</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
Since we are considering probability measures over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>, it is not enough to just define a mapping between spaces. Explicitly, say that we are considering the two probability measures <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \sim  \mathrm {Unif}[0,1]]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \sim  \mathrm {Unif}[0,2]]]></fr:tex>. Trivially, we have the mapping <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : [0, 1] \to  [0,2]]]></fr:tex> given by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x) \mapsto  2x]]></fr:tex>.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
<fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/D8LA/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>D8LA</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/D8LA/</fr:route><fr:title text="Definitions FM">Definitions <fr:link href="/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" title="Flow Matching for Generative Modeling" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" display-uri="lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023" type="local">FM</fr:link></fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>1</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/008B/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>008B</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/008B/</fr:route><fr:title text="Probablity density path">Probablity density path</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>The <html:em>probability density path</html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p: [0,1] \times  \mathbb {R}^d \to  \mathbb {R}_{>0}]]></fr:tex> is a time dependent probability density function i.e. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\int  p_t(x)\mathrm {d}x = 1]]></fr:tex></html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>1</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/008C/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>008C</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/008C/</fr:route><fr:title text="Time-dependent vector field">Time-dependent vector field</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>We define a <html:em>time-dependent vector field</html:em> as a map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v: [0,1] \times  \mathbb {R}^d \to  \mathbb {R}^d]]></fr:tex></html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>1</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/008D/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>008D</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/008D/</fr:route><fr:title text="Flow">Flow</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>Give a <fr:link href="/008C/" title="Time-dependent vector field" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008C/" display-uri="008C" type="local">vector field</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v_t]]></fr:tex> one can construct a time-dependent diffeomorphic map called a <html:em>flow</html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi : [0,1] \times  \mathbb {R}^d \to  \mathbb {R}^d]]></fr:tex> defined via the ordinary differential equation
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align*}
  \frac {\mathrm {d}}{\mathrm {d}t} \phi _t(x) &= v_t(\phi _t(x)) \\
  \phi _{0}(x) &= x
.\end {align*}]]></fr:tex></html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 <html:div class="jms-callout" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.7);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.05);
  "><html:span style="font-weight: 600; color: rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.7);">Remark.</html:span> 
   Modeling a <fr:link href="/008C/" title="Time-dependent vector field" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008C/" display-uri="008C" type="local">vector field</fr:link> via a neural network i.e. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v_t(x; \theta )]]></fr:tex> implicitly defines a deep parametric model of the flow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi _t(x)]]></fr:tex> via solving the ODE or an approximation, such as
   <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\phi _{t + \Delta  t}(x) \approx  \phi _t(x) + \Delta  t \cdot  v_t(\phi _t(x); \theta )]]></fr:tex>
   Obviously, accuracy will be dependent on the step size <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta  t]]></fr:tex>.
 </html:div>
<fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/008E/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>008E</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/008E/</fr:route><fr:title text="Generated probability paths">Generated probability paths</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>We say that a <fr:link href="/008C/" title="Time-dependent vector field" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008C/" display-uri="008C" type="local">vector field</fr:link> <html:em>generates</html:em> a <fr:link href="/008B/" title="Probablity density path" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008B/" display-uri="008B" type="local">probability density path</fr:link> if the <fr:link href="/008D/" title="Flow" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008D/" display-uri="008D" type="local">flow</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v_t]]></fr:tex> satisfies
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[p_t = [\phi _t]_* p_{0},]]></fr:tex>
where
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[[\phi _t]_*p_{0}(x) = p_{0}(\phi _t^{-1}(x)) \det \left [ \frac {\partial  \phi _t^{-1} }{\partial  x}(x) \right ].  ]]></fr:tex></html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>2</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/008I/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>008I</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/008I/</fr:route><fr:title text="Generation via Continuity Equation">Generation via Continuity Equation</fr:title><fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>
A <fr:link href="/008C/" title="Time-dependent vector field" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008C/" display-uri="008C" type="local">vector field</fr:link> generates a <fr:link href="/008B/" title="Probablity density path" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008B/" display-uri="008B" type="local">probability density path</fr:link> if it satisfies the <fr:link href="/EFN0/" title="Continuity Equation" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/EFN0/" display-uri="EFN0" type="local">continuity equation</fr:link>.
</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>9</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/LRL4/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>LRL4</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/LRL4/</fr:route><fr:title text="Flow Matching Loss"><fr:link href="/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" title="Flow Matching for Generative Modeling" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" display-uri="lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023" type="local">Flow Matching</fr:link> Loss</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>Given an initial noise distribution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, a desired data distribution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>, a <fr:link href="/008B/" title="Probablity density path" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008B/" display-uri="008B" type="local">probability density path</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_t]]></fr:tex>, such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_{0} = p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_{1} =q]]></fr:tex>, and a <fr:link href="/008C/" title="Time-dependent vector field" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008C/" display-uri="008C" type="local">vector field</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_t]]></fr:tex> that <fr:link href="/008E/" title="Generated probability paths" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008E/" display-uri="008E" type="local">generates</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_t]]></fr:tex>. We define the <html:em>flow matching loss</html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}_{\mathrm {FM}}]]></fr:tex> as
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}_{\mathrm {FM}}(\theta ) \coloneqq  \mathbb {E}_{t, p_t(x)} \|v_t(x; \theta ) - u_t\|]]></fr:tex></html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:contributor><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>2</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/008F/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>008F</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/008F/</fr:route><fr:title text="Conditioning Trick FM ">Conditioning Trick <fr:link href="/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" title="Flow Matching for Generative Modeling" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" display-uri="lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023" type="local">FM</fr:link> </fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p> Given data distribution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q(x)]]></fr:tex>, we define an approximation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)]]></fr:tex> with the form <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[p(x) = \int  p(x \mid  x_1) q(x_1) \mathrm {d}x_{1}]]></fr:tex> In order to ensure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x) \approx  q(x)]]></fr:tex>, we pick <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x \mid  x_{1})]]></fr:tex> that concentrates around <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{1}]]></fr:tex> i.e. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x \mid  x_{1}) \sim  N(x \mid  x_{1}, \sigma ^2 I)]]></fr:tex> for small <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>.
 </html:p><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>9</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/8XAJ/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>8XAJ</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/8XAJ/</fr:route><fr:title text="Conditional Vector Field">Conditional Vector Field</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>
 We define the <html:em>conditional vector field</html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v_t(\cdot  \mid  x_{1})]]></fr:tex> as the <fr:link href="/008C/" title="Time-dependent vector field" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008C/" display-uri="008C" type="local">vector field</fr:link> that <fr:link href="/008E/" title="Generated probability paths" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008E/" display-uri="008E" type="local">generates</fr:link> the conditional <fr:link href="/008E/" title="Generated probability paths" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008E/" display-uri="008E" type="local">probability path</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_t(x \mid  x_{1})]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>9</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/373T/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>373T</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/373T/</fr:route><fr:title text="Marginal Vector Field">Marginal Vector Field</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>
 Given a <fr:link href="/8XAJ/" title="Conditional Vector Field" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/8XAJ/" display-uri="8XAJ" type="local">conditional vector field</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v_t(x \mid  x_{1})]]></fr:tex> we define the <html:em>marginal vector field</html:em> as <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[v_t(x) = \int  v_t(x \mid  x_1) \frac {p(x \mid  x_1) q(x_{1})}{p(t)}]]></fr:tex></html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>9</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/93R8/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>93R8</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/93R8/</fr:route><fr:title text="Marginal Generation">Marginal Generation</fr:title><fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>Given a <fr:link href="/8XAJ/" title="Conditional Vector Field" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/8XAJ/" display-uri="8XAJ" type="local">conditional vector field</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v_t(x \mid  x_{1})]]></fr:tex> that <fr:link href="/008E/" title="Generated probability paths" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008E/" display-uri="008E" type="local">generates</fr:link> the conditional <fr:link href="/008B/" title="Probablity density path" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008B/" display-uri="008B" type="local">probability path</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_t(x \mid  x_{1})]]></fr:tex>
 then the <fr:link href="/373T/" title="Marginal Vector Field" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/373T/" display-uri="373T" type="local">marginal vector field</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v_t]]></fr:tex> generates <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_t]]></fr:tex>, where
 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[p_t(x) = \int  p_t(x \mid  x_1) q(x_{1})]]></fr:tex></html:p>
 <html:div class="jms-callout" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.03);
  "><html:span style="font-weight: 600; color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);">Proof.</html:span> 
  This follows from just plugging into <fr:link href="/EFN0/" title="Continuity Equation" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/EFN0/" display-uri="EFN0" type="local">continuity equation</fr:link>.
</html:div>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>9</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/DZ1D/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>DZ1D</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/DZ1D/</fr:route><fr:title text="FM Gradient Equivalence"><fr:link href="/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" title="Flow Matching for Generative Modeling" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" display-uri="lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023" type="local">FM</fr:link> Gradient Equivalence</fr:title><fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <html:div class="jms-callout" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.03);
  "><html:span style="font-weight: 600; color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);">Proof.</html:span> 

</html:div>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><html:p>which is supposedly a "good" approximation of the data distribution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>. We can then show that a <html:em>conditional flow matching loss</html:em> has the same gradient as the full <html:em>flow matching loss</html:em> i.e. our vector field should converge to the <html:em>marginal vector field</html:em>, which is a good approximation for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>.
 </html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><html:p>To generate samples, we integrate the <html:strong>vector field</html:strong></html:p><html:p><html:strong style="font-family: var(--sans); font-weight: 500;">Important.</html:strong> We do not <html:em>have</html:em> the flow. We only have the flow for a <html:strong>given</html:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{1}]]></fr:tex>. This can then provide a target for the vector field with equivalent gradient.</html:p><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/TGWF/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>TGWF</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/TGWF/</fr:route><fr:title text="Flow Matching vs. Diffusion">Flow Matching vs. Diffusion</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>Notes and thoughts from blog <fr:link href="/gaoDiffusionMeetsFlow2024/" title="Diffusion Meets Flow Matching: Two Sides of the Same Coin" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/gaoDiffusionMeetsFlow2024/" display-uri="gaoDiffusionMeetsFlow2024" type="local">Diffusion Meets Flow Matching: Two Sides of the Same Coin</fr:link>. As a useful pre-requisite, I recommend my notes on <fr:link href="/007T/" title="Diffusion Models" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/007T/" display-uri="007T" type="local">diffusion</fr:link> and <fr:link href="/008A/" title="Flow Matching: What, Why, and How?" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/008A/" display-uri="008A" type="local">flow matching</fr:link> respectively.</html:p><html:p>To start, I began looking into this due to the wildly empirical claims from <fr:link href="/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" title="Flow Matching for Generative Modeling" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" display-uri="lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023" type="local">Flow Matching for Generative Modeling</fr:link>. Namely,</html:p>
 <html:blockquote class="jms-quote" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.6em 1.1em 0.6em 1.3em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.25);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.035);
  font-style: italic;
  color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.85);
  ">
  <html:ul><html:li><html:em>"We find that using FM provides more robust and stable training, and achieves superior performance compared to score matching."</html:em></html:li>
   <html:li><html:em>"Furthermore, we find that our models produce better trade-offs between computational cost and sample quality."</html:em></html:li></html:ul>
 </html:blockquote>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter>
